🔷 What is System Design ?
system design , designing day to day tech system jaise, whatsapp,instagram,uber. aise hee chijo ko thing krna market ke according or design krna.
System Design Pattern ek proven architectural solution hota hai jo large-scale software systems ki common problems solve karta hai
jaise:
 - scalability
 - maintainability
 - availability
 - fault tolerance
 - performance
Ye code-level pattern (Singleton, Factory) se bada hota hai,Ye poore system ka structure define karta hai.

                                                        System Design 
                                             ______________|    |____________
                                            |                                |
                        HLD ________________|                                |_________________ LLD
High level Desing :
iske ander hum over view of the system ko design krte hai
- for eg - agr whatsapp design krna hai to kon sa database use kr rhe honge, message queue ko use krenge,cache etc.
- system ke different-different component ko btate hai ki , kis trh se design hoga. isme koi code nhi krna hota

Low level Desgin:
actual machine coding krni hoti hai jaise:
- design API
- class diagram v bnate hai
- models ko v btate hai

let's assume apko netflix jaise system ko / netflix ko design krna hai: jisme millions of people video ko watch kr paye across different simultineously.
isko requirment ko smjhne ke liye or ache se hme 2 chijo ko smjhna pdega:
(1) functional requirment :- exact kon sa feature ko build krne ki jarurt hai jise user aa ke use kr ske. jaise:
- users can signup & login
- users can buy a subscription
- user can play & pause the video.
(2) non-functional requirment :- hmara system kis tarike se perform krega,uske ander kya kya qualities hogi,jaise:
- secure system with authentication / autherization 
- low latency for video ( video play hone me jyda time n lge).
- scalable system ( millions of user watch kr paye).

High level Desgin : step by step component/concept to learn 
steps 1 : fundamentals
- serverless vs serverfull
- horizental vs vertical scalling
- what are threads?
- what are pages?
- how does the internet works?
step 2 : databases
- sql vs noSQL dbs 
- in memory dbs
- data replication & migration
- data partitioning
- sharding
step 3: consistency vs availability
- data consistency & its levels
- isolation & its levels
- CAP theorem
step 4 : cache
- what is cache ( redis,memcahed)
- write policies : write back , through & around
- replacement Policies : LFU,LRU , segmented LRU etc.
- content delivery networks (CDNs).
step 5 : networking
- TCP vs UDP
- what is http (1/2/3) & https
- websockets
- webRTC & video streaming
step 6 : load balancers
- load balancing algorithms ( stateless & stateful )
- consistent hashing
- proxy & reverse proxy
- rate limiting
step 7 : message queue
- asynchrous processing ( kafka , rabbit mq)
- publisher - subscriber model
step 8 : monoliths vs microservices 
- why microservices
- concept of 'single point of failure'
- avoiding cascading failures
- containerization (Docker)
- migerating to microservices
step 9 : monitoring & logging
- logging events & monitoring metrics
- anomaly detection
step 10 : security 
- token for auth
- sso & oAuth
- access control lists & rule engines
- encryption
step 11 : system desing tradeoffs
- push vs pull architecture
- consistency vs availability
- sql vs no-sql dbs
- memory vs latency
- throughput vs latency
- accuracy vs latency
step 12 : practice popular platform
- instagram 
-youtube
- tweeter
- netflix
- user etc.

low level design :  
step 1 : oops programming
- encapsulation 
- abstraction
- inheritance
- polymorphism
- solid principles
step 2 : design pattern 
- creational desing pattern ( single, factory etc.)
- structural ( proxy, bridge etc)
- behavioral ( strategy , command, observer etc.)
step 3 : concurrency & thread safety 
- thread safe injection
- locking mechanism
- producer-consumer
- race condition & synchronization
step 4 : UML diagrams
step 5 : APIs
- api design
- request/response object modeling
- versioning & extensibility
- clean code principles : DRY,SRP etc.
- Avoiding God classes

